SIMPLE: manage
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Manage
<hw>Man"age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>man⟦egrave⟧ge</ets>, It. <ets>maneggio</ets>, fr.
<ets>maneggiare</ets> to manage, fr. L. <ets>manus</ets>hand. Perhaps
somewhat influenced by F. <ets>m⟦eacute⟧nage</ets> housekeeping, OF.
<ets>mesnage</ets>, akin to E. <ets>mansion</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>,
and cf. <er>Manege</er>.]</ety> <def>The handling or government of
anything, but esp. of a horse; management; administration. See
<er>Manege</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Young men, in the conduct and <qex>manage</qex> of actions,
embrace more than they can hold.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Down, down I come; like glistering Phaethon⟦br⟧
Wanting the <qex>manage</qex> of unruly jades.</q>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The unlucky <qex>manage</qex> of this fatal brawl.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word, in its limited sense of management of a
horse, has been displaced by <xex>manege</xex>; in its more general
meaning, by <xex>management</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manage</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Manage
<hw>Man"age</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Managed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Managing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From
<er>Manage</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have under
control and direction; to conduct; to guide; to administer; to treat; to
handle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Long tubes are cumbersome, and scarce to be easily
<qex>managed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What wars I<qex>manage</qex>, and what wreaths I gain.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence, Esp.:</specif> <def>to guide by careful or
delicate treatment; to wield with address; to make subservient by artful
conduct; to bring around cunningly to one's plans.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was so much his interest to <qex>manage</qex> his Protestant
subjects.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was not her humor to <qex>manage</qex> those over whom she had
gained an ascendant.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hurd.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To train in the manege, as a horse; to exercise in
graceful or artful action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To treat with care; to husband.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To bring about; to contrive.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To direct; govern; control; wield; order;
contrive; concert; conduct; transact.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manage</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Manage
<hw>Man"age</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To direct affairs; to carry on
business or affairs; to administer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leave them to <qex>manage</qex> for thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manageability</ent>⟦br⟧
